page.title: 11Buildings in Dowlish Wake.
page.content: Dowlish Wake is a small village with several interesting domestic buildings. The Manor House, parts of which probably date from the 16th C, stands on the hill close to the church. The internal and external details are very fine . Its smoke blackened roof has windbraces, a dentillated cornice plate and pendants. The internal details include framed ceilings and hamstone fireplaces. The external decorative details and window mullions are also of ham stone. The roof is thatched. The Old Parsonage is only a fragment of a much larger 16th C house. Higher Farm, a very tall house with a fine cut ham stone front, and mullion windows. It has a very unusual double stair, and good timber partitions.
